    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There's also `[System.Environment]::CurrentDirectory` ðŸ˜„ \r\n\r\n(Can be both `{get; set;}` )\r\n\r\nWhich does reflect the currently active directory of the process itself (i.e. pwsh.exe) when changed with the `SetCurrentDirectory()` static method.\r\n\r\nI always thought that this was by design, because PowerShell has this notion of runspaces, and what you see as the `gl | pwd | $PWD` is the currently active directory in only the currently active runspace.\r\n\r\nThat said, I have some sympathy for this change...\r\n\r\nBecause there's this one time (I guess we all could tell similar stories here) where a script I wrote tripped over the path given as a parameter value to a static method of a .NET type I was using, like [IO.File]::ReadLines , or [Net.WebClient]::DownloadFile ...\r\n\r\nðŸ˜„ \r\n\r\nAlways had to remember to use full path names in such cases.",
